WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.820
By now, you know our process, our offer, and
how to handle objections when sellers push

2
00:00:05.820 --> 00:00:06.320
back.

3
00:00:06.620 --> 00:00:12.920
But sellers also ask straightforward
questions, not objections, just questions, and

4
00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:15.420
how you answer those matters just as much.

5
00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:19.760
The goal here is not to memorize a list of
answers.

6
00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:25.600
It's to understand what the seller is really
asking underneath the words, and to respond

7
00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:28.440
with confidence and clarity in your own
voice.

8
00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:32.000
Every seller question maps back to one of
three things.

9
00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:35.000
Can I trust you? Am I getting a fair deal?

10
00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:37.100
Is this going to be complicated?

11
00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:43.120
If your answer addresses whichever one of
those is actually driving the question, the

12
00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:45.700
specific words you use matter a lot less.

13
00:00:46.900 --> 00:00:51.620
Here are the 10 questions that come up most
often, and how to think about each one.

14
00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:56.360
How does this work? This is someone who
wants simplicity.

15
00:00:56.700 --> 00:00:59.180
They don't want a 10-minute explanation.

16
00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:01.980
They want to know the basic flow.

17
00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:04.840
Keep it short. We have a conversation.

18
00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:06.960
Our team evaluates the property.

19
00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:08.820
We put together a cash offer.

20
00:01:09.180 --> 00:01:11.580
And if it works for you, we handle the
closing.

21
00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:13.780
No repairs needed on your end.

22
00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:16.600
No commissions. We take care of the
paperwork.

23
00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:17.700
That's it.

24
00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:20.580
If they want more detail, they'll ask.

25
00:01:21.770 --> 00:01:23.390
How do you come up with the offer?

26
00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:26.440
They want to know it's not a random number.

27
00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:31.180
Tell them you look at what similar houses in
their area have actually sold for.

28
00:01:31.488 --> 00:01:35.868
You factor in the condition of the property
and what repairs would cost, and you come up

29
00:01:35.868 --> 00:01:37.773
with a number that works for both sides.

30
00:01:38.100 --> 00:01:43.380
Keep it simple. Don't say ARV or MAO formula
or any of that.

31
00:01:43.420 --> 00:01:45.540
Just say it like a normal person would.

32
00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:49.900
Is this a scam? This comes from a real
place.

33
00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:53.600
They've probably had bad experiences or at
least heard stories.

34
00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:56.880
Don't get defensive. Say you understand the
caution.

35
00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:59.660
Everything goes through a licensed title
company.

36
00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:03.160
They'll have attorney review available on
all the paperwork.

37
00:02:03.700 --> 00:02:06.060
You never ask for money up front.

38
00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:08.300
They never pay you anything.

39
00:02:08.680 --> 00:02:08.930
Ever.

40
00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:13.420
And you're happy to share your company
information so they can look you up before

41
00:02:13.420 --> 00:02:14.860
anything moves forward.

42
00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:17.560
Why can't you offer more?

43
00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:20.160
They want to feel like the deal is fair.

44
00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:22.820
And right now it doesn't feel fair to them.

45
00:02:23.300 --> 00:02:24.420
Explain the trade-off.

46
00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:26.780
You're buying the property as is.

47
00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:32.740
You're taking on all the risk, all the
repair costs, and all the carrying costs.

48
00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:37.600
The reason the price is what it is, is
because of what they get in return.

49
00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:40.800
Speed. Certainty. No hassle.

50
00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:43.780
No commissions. That's the exchange.

51
00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:46.080
Some people will get it.

52
00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:47.400
Some won't.

53
00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:49.960
How fast can you close?

54
00:02:50.588 --> 00:02:54.731
They're trying to figure out if you can
actually solve their problem on their timeline.

55
00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:59.500
Tell them as fast as a couple of weeks if
they need to move quickly or on whatever

56
00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.020
timeline works for them.

57
00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:02.820
They pick the closing date.

58
00:03:02.900 --> 00:03:04.420
We work around it.

59
00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:08.740
All right, that's the first five questions,
decoded.

60
00:03:09.160 --> 00:03:11.280
Next up, the other five repairs.

61
00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:13.800
Fees. What happens after they sign?

62
00:03:14.200 --> 00:03:15.920
And what to say when a seller asks,

63
00:03:16.260 --> 00:03:17.500
What if I change my mind?

64
00:03:17.697 --> 00:03:18.602
I'll see you there.
